<h2>What Moves Your ICU Salary Above the State Average</h2>
<h3>Unit Type</h3>
<p>CVICU typically commands 10-18% above MICU average in the same hospital. Trauma ICU and Neuro ICU follow closely. MICU is usually the baseline rate for critical care.</p>

<h3>Certification</h3>
<p>CCRN certification adds $2,000-$8,000 per year in hospitals with clinical ladder programs. It also qualifies you for better travel contracts and makes you competitive for charge and flight nursing roles.</p>

<h3>Shift Differential</h3>
<p>Night differential at most hospitals runs 12-20% above base. Weekend differentials add another 10-15%. A $85,000 base nurse working mostly nights and weekends routinely clears $100,000 without overtime.</p>

<h3>Charge Pay</h3>
<p>Charge nurse differential typically runs $3-6/hour above staff rate. In smaller ICUs where every senior nurse rotates charge, this adds $7,000-$11,000/year.</p>

